I don't believe this 30-day heads-up [1] necessarily increases the probability of an ADIZ, though it certainly seems to bait one. Had Japan sponsored this tour with less or no notice, then maybe the increase of tensions afterwards would slightly increase the likelihood of an ADIZ. This IFP exhausted me in Season 4. Based on how sudden the ECS ADIZ was established in '13 (and subsequently shallowly enforced), I had predicted (confidently) the SCS ADIZ would go up last year, obviously I was wrong; this in spite of all of the activity taking place in the SCS over the last 9 months.  Regarding many forecasters' decreasing their probabilities based on the 'passage of time': is that because you don't believe the SCS ADIZ is a certainty at all, or you just don't believe 8.5 months is enough to see this occur? The ECS ADIZ was established (ostensibly) within a months 'notice'. Meanwhile, we've been hawking this SCS ADIZ issue for at least two years now. Doesn't it seem the SCS ADIZ is inevitable, meaning the passage of time would increase likelihood? Or are you counting on the wizards of diplomacy interfering with inevitably. (The US is actually sharing a table with China in Pakistan today (the 11th) to deal (literally) with the Taliban. I can see the US sharing a hookah with China, "...at least we're landlocked here and don't have to worry about pesky Sea ADIZs. (winkyface, puff puff)" Just spit-ballin', and trying to keep in mind KJU is going to always throw toddler temper tantrums, complicating any calculated focus and predictions on the SCS...at least for me. [1] (http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/japans-maritime-self-defence-force-to-cover-more-of-south-china-sea-sources)
[2] (http://thediplomat.com/2013/11/china-imposes-restrictions-on-air-space-over-senkaku-islands/) ~technical question for anyone~ 
